Majorities of women in the country's key cities as well as some regions believe abortion is morally acceptable in instances of rape or incest, maternal health risk, and risks to the fetus' life.

Women in Mozambique hold more liberal attitudes toward abortion than their male peers, but they exhibit a strong desire for greater reproductive rights. Although abortion is allowed in cases of rape or incest, health risk to the mother, and life or severe disability risk to the fetus, few women believe the procedure should be legal in those instances. The majority of women in Mozambique favor accessing the procedure safely and legally despite existing policies that make these circumstances nearly impossible.

At least half of Nepalese men and half of women in the Rift Valley regions believe abortion is morally acceptable for three-quarters of nine potential circumstances in which the procedure would be needed. Adolescents and their mothers are most likely to accept abortion in cases of risk to the mother's life or health or severe health risk to the fetus. Because Nepalese abortion law is extremely restrictive, people's attitudes toward abortion often take precedence over their knowledge of the law.
